'''Förvaltningsaktiebolaget Stattum''', a Swedish government holding company that can be characterized as a [[National Wealth Fund]]. It was set up in 1991, to manage the listed shareholdings of the Swedish government, following the dismantling of [[Fortia ab|Fortia AB]] and [[Statsföretag]]. Shareholdings included [[Saab Group|Celsius Industrier AB]],  [[:sv:Sveaskog|AssiDomän]], [[SSAB]], and [[Pharmacia|Pharmacia & Upjohn]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://data.riksdagen.se/fil/08D0FF12-7902-4165-A054-A8643A4C851B | title=Ekonomisk värde och samhällsnytta – förslag till en ny statlig ägarförvaltning | publisher=[[Statens offentliga utredningar|SOU]] 2012:14 | year=2012 | location=Stockholm |language=sv | isbn=978-91-38-23700-7| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117063423/https://data.riksdagen.se/fil/08D0FF12-7902-4165-A054-A8643A4C851B | archivedate=November 17, 2016 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>

Stattum played a leading role when the [[Swedish government]] made the first attempt by a European government to address systematically the ownership and management of government enterprises in 1998-2001.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://media.publicwealthofnations.com/2016/11/Privatisation-International-Euromoney.pdf | title=Sweden: bold, novel approach | publisher=[[Euromoney|Euromoney Institutional Investor]] | work=Privatisation International | date=December 2000 | accessdate=June 23, 2018 | author=[[James Sassoon]] and Martin Pellback, [[UBS Warburg]]}}</ref>

